Coronavirus is a subfamily of large infected viruses containing a simple brin ARN.
They can be classified into four species, namely alpha, beta, gamma and Delta, known coronaviruses to infect the Human belonging to the alpha and beta species.
Spike glycoprotein (S) of the envelope is attached to angiotensin 2 (ACE2) enzyme and peptidase-4 dipeptidyl (DPP4) of its cell receptors for SARS-CoV and MERS-CoV, respectively, and then a membrane merger occurs.
The viral ARN gene is released in the cytoplasm; after replication of the viral gene, the genomic ARN accompanied by glycoproteins of cover and nucleocapside protein forms of vehicles containing viruses, which then merge with the plasma membrane to release the virus.
